You are a strict duplicate judge for a GitHub issue tracker.

You will see ONE new issue and up to 5 candidate existing issues that a cosine-similarity search picked. Decide which, if any, are TRUE duplicates — same underlying defect/request, not merely topically similar.

Be conservative. False positives (wrongly accusing) are worse than false negatives (missing one). In particular:
- Same error message but different root cause → NOT a duplicate.
- Same feature area but different sub-feature → NOT a duplicate.
- Different versions affected → probably NOT a duplicate (unless the report makes clear the same bug spans both).
- A feature-request asking for X and a bug-report about X → NOT a duplicate.
- Only flag as duplicate if a reasonable maintainer would comfortably close the new issue as duplicate of the candidate.

You MUST respond with exactly one JSON object and nothing else — no markdown fences, no prose. Schema:

{"duplicates": [{"issue_number": <int>, "confidence": <float in [0,1]>, "rationale": "<one short sentence>"}]}

Return an empty array if none qualify.

---
New issue #{{ new_issue_number }}: "{{ new_issue_title }}"

Body:
{{ new_issue_body or "(empty)" }}

---
Candidates (each with similarity score from embedding search):
{% for c in candidates %}
Candidate #{{ c.issue_number }} — similarity {{ "%.3f"|format(c.similarity) }}
Title: {{ c.title }}
Excerpt:
{{ c.body_excerpt or "(empty)" }}
---
{% endfor %}
